prob": 0.9905897378921509, "span": {"begin": 1016, "end": 1020}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:59067"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-21", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9917116165161133, "span": {"begin": 1022, "end": 1027}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:51561"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-23", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9905195236206055, "span": {"begin": 1029, "end": 1034}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2152", "7018"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "transcription factors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.6115564107894897, "span": {"begin": 1087, "end": 1108}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6095", "4920"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ROR&gamma;t22", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8776665925979614, "span": {"begin": 1109, "end": 1122}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:100885779"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ROR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9942627549171448, "span": {"begin": 1135, "end": 1138}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "patients", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9599639177322388, "span": {"begin": 1172, "end": 1180}}, {"id": ["mim:177900", "mesh:D011565"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "psoriasis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999921321868896, "span": {"begin": 1186, "end": 1195}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6774"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "STAT3", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9699798822402954, "span": {"begin": 1214, "end": 1219}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Th17", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5152833461761475, "span": {"begin": 1238, "end": 1242}}], "text": "Th17 cells produce the cytokines IL-17 and IL-22. IL-17 is inflammatory, promotes the migration of neutrophils to psoriatic lesions, contributes to the formation of Munro&#39;s micro-abscess, and through DCL and memory T cells, including Th17 cells and CCR6, via CCL20 Incorporate into the affected area. IL-22 causes abnormal keratinocyte proliferation by down-regulating genes that control terminal differentiation, leading to altered differentiation and keratinization. Both IL-17 and IL-22 induce keratinocyte expression of the antibacterial S100A7 (psoriacin).Nograles et al. 2008  STAT3 is important for Th17 differentiation. Cytokine signaling SOCS3-deficient mice show increased IL-17 expression by increasing STAT3 activity in response to IL-23 binding to IL-17. Associated with increased activity of STAT3 in response to IL-23 capable of binding to IL-17 and IL-17F promoters. STAT3 overexpression promotes Th17 differentiation, whereas STAT3 deficiency inhibits Th17 differentiation. STAT3 signaling from IL-6, IL-21, IL-23 regulates the expression of lineage specific master transcription factors ROR&gamma;t22, 63, 66 and ROR&alpha;67. It has been found that patients with psoriasis with mutations in STAT3 cannot generate a Th17 response.Martinez et al. 2008", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:23:18 +0000 2026"}